{"add":{"doc":{"id":"fabe4cefeeacc4b2eeb848f568fd27d5db74566514d442344a1df94e5b9d590a","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Galen_detail.jpg/115px-Galen_detail.jpg","previous":["Portal:Science/Featured biography/7"],"after":["Claudius Galenus of Pergamum (129-200 AD), better known in English as Galen, was an ancient Greek physician. His views dominated European medicine for over a thousand years. From the modern viewpoint, Galen's theories were partially correct and partially flawed: he demonstrated that arteries carry blood rather than air, and conducted the first studies of nerve, brain, and heart function. He also argued that the mind was in the brain, not in the heart as Aristotle had claimed."]}}}